# Forward PWAs still re-fetching the old hashed manifest URL (now gone)
# to the stable path. `_redirects` fire even when no asset matches.
# Removable in ~a month, once most installs have refreshed.
#
# Anchor the match to the `.webmanifest` extension: a bare `manifest-*`
# splat also swallows hashed route chunks like `manifest-route-<hash>.js`
# (301'd to JSON, they break the gallery's dynamic import). The `:hash`
# placeholder matches any non-`/` run — hyphenated hashes included — while
# the trailing literal keeps it scoped to the old manifest asset.
/_build/assets/manifest-:hash.webmanifest  /manifest.webmanifest  301

# The `/logs/:file` viewer is a client route — its file names only exist
# at runtime, so no per-file HTML is prerendered. Rewrite every session
# URL onto the one prerendered shell (`/logs/session`, see the nitro
# `prerender.routes` list in `vite.config.ts`) so a hard load or refresh
# serves a real route-shaped shell instead of falling through to the 404
# page; the client router then renders the actual file. A 200 rewrite
# (not a redirect) keeps the session URL in the address bar.
#
# Anchor the match to the `.ndjson` suffix every log file carries (the
# `:file` placeholder matches the non-`/` run, the literal scopes it).
# A bare `/logs/*` splat would also swallow the list at `/logs/` and the
# shell itself, looping. Target the shell's canonical directory URL
# (`/logs/session/`, not `/index.html`) — Cloudflare canonicalizes
# `index.html` to the trailing-slash form, so aiming at the file turns
# the in-place rewrite into a redirect that rewrites the address bar.
/logs/:file.ndjson  /logs/session/  200
